étis existence. They talk about the arduous journey to rebuild the Métis nation from a once-marginalized and defeated people; their accounts ranging from personal reflections on identity to tales of advocacy against poverty and poor housing, and for the recognition of Métis rights. Métis Rising is an extraordinary work that exemplifies how contemporary Métis identity has been forged into a force to be reckoned with.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Indigenous Studies.2bisacsh1 aAnuik, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartlett, Judith G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellehumeur-Kearns, Laura-Lee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyer, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreaton, Curtis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartrand, Larry, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aChartrand, Larry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChartrand, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorion, Leah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKermoal, Nathalie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKress, Margaret, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLittlejohn, Catherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLogan, Tricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPratt, Yvonne Poitras, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStevenson, Allyson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVizina, Yvonne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo